text: Is there any evidence of black aristocrats in Scotland or England in the 1500s? This seems inaccurate to me, although I am aware of notable black aristos/notables in Russia (Abram Petrovish Gannibal, the grandfather of poet Alexander Pushkin) and France (Thomas-Alexandre Dumas, the father of novelist Alexander Dumas), but the only one I know of in British history is Dido Elizabeth Belle...and all of those people were in the 18th century, 200 years after the events portrayed here. It strikes me as highly unlikely that there would be SO many in aristocratic circles at the time. Aside from the questionable history, it also seems rather patronising. I didn't mind it in Beauty and the Beast, since that is a fantasy film (if you can accept men turning into beasts and people bursting into song, then why not...), but this - aside from the 2 queens not actually meeting - appears to be aiming for a realist approach, and such blatant inaccuracy takes one right out of the film.

text: Elizabeth and Mary never met in person and they were never friends. It looks like they're trying to Mary the sweet, poor victim . Yes, Elizabeth could be vicious (she had to be) and she kept Mary under house arrest, but Mary often schemed against Elizabeth and may have been in at least one assassination plot. Also while Elizabeth was a competent and cunning - if sometimes ruthless - ruler, Mary was overly emotional, not to bright, and had little common sense. It's worth mentioning that while Mary did wear lead-based white makeup to hide her small pox scars it wasn't the severe clown white in the thumbnail. Her wife were red, but that artificial orange is hilariously cartoon like. She looks like Pennywise, not Elizabeth I.

text: People are complaining about the black and Asian courtiers in this film, but I have spotted far bigger historical in accuracies.  1. Elizabeth and Mary never met, they only communicated through letters and through their ambassadors to one another‚Äôs countries. 2. Mary did not grow up in Scotland, there for she would not have had anything close to a Scottish accent. 3. By the time Mary was executed she had been through so much that she had looked a couple of decades older than her actual age, she had grey hair, and just like  Elizabeth, she wore wigs on a regular basis.   Also, though not at all common in the aristocracy, there were quite a few people of ‚Äúexotic‚Äù origin in the courts of European monarchs, particularly as handmaids, and things of other things of that nature. And as far as black people go, there was this group of black people called the Moors that controlled the Iberian Peninsula for nearly 700 years, they had also managed to spread out across Europe, even (sporadically) in the northern most parts of the continent.

text: Mary actually would have had a French accent, considering that she was raised in France. Without context the French accent would seem weird to people who don't know.

text: As lush as this looks, I'm afraid it's going to be painful to sit through for scholars and aficionados of Tudor history. We know for a fact that Elizabeth and Mary never met in person. And yet, just like the 1971 version of the same story starring Vanessa Redgrave as Mary and Glenda Jackson as Elizabeth, the producers cannot resist coercing the writers to create a confrontational scene between them. I guess they think the real-life story isn't powerful enough on its own without their skillful confabulation. I will definitely have to see it because as a lover of all things Tudor - and English - I will be unable to stay away. But I know I am going to cringe throughout the entire thing as liberties are taken with history and reality is distorted for the sake of dramatic effect.

text: One would have hoped that with the passage of time a more truthful version of the life of Mary Queen of Scots would have emerged.   Alas, No.   This film is based on a book on her life by John Guy who claimed he was at last producing the truthful version.   Yes, he covered the night of the murder of Darnley and admitted there was nothing that implicated Mary, but he added that SHE MUST HAVE BEEN IMPLICATED.  So he could not bring himself to the truthful and honest statement that perhaps she was innocent.     So much for truthful objective history..   On the trial of Mary by Elizabeth again like every other modern historian he will not quite from any of the 'copies' of the letters that Mary is alleged to have sent to Babbington.   Perhaps this is because he would have been tempted to ask for the originals in Mary's handwriting.   He did not want to to there because he feared that he would have discovered that such original letters did not exist.     So in the end John Guy was a 'go with the flow' historian.     Mary is the most lied about figure in history.

text: Guys! It's not a documentary, it's a drama. If they displayed it as an actual biography, things would be different, but the film is based on a book called "My Heart Is My Own: The Life of Mary Queen of Scots", which was sold as a "dramatic reinterpretation". So relax, they knew it wasn't supposed to be accurate from the moment this thing entered pre-production. I'm honestly more interested in performances and settings with this one. It looks like even if it doesn't turn out that great, Robbie is once again proving she's much more than a pretty face, as she is willing to look the way she does here and still is captivating from the few seconds we see her in the trailer.   I will agree however that it makes little to no sense having black people in authority positions when considering the slave trade history which hasn't taken place yet. It's about as distracting as having Scandinavians in positions of power in 5th Century Japan.

text: I get why they're not going according to history because Hollywood, but I'm not sure why they aren't. The history between Mary and Elizabeth has so much story behind it that it is almost relevant to today's society (eg. the tensions between religion, and women position in power/parliament). The reason why Elizabeth and Mary hated each other (whether they wanted to or not) is because they threatened each other's position as Queens - because of religion and ability to produce heirs. Elizabeth was always threatened on the throne because the men in high positions did not like a woman in power and wanted to replace her with Mary. Also, it can also show a story of the unfortunate positions women have in power where they feel like they are always competing (who's better than the other? Which one should we get rid of? etc)

text: This is some real nonsense! Just for starters, Mary Queen of Scots spoke and used French as her primary language, France being where she spent the best years of her life (ages 5-19)--so what's with the phony Scottish accent? She spent only seven years in Scotland, an impoverished country she didn't even value all that highly after her pampered years at the French court. Also, she never even MET Elizabeth I. And no mention whatsoever of her Catholicism versus Elizabeth's Protestantism? This movie can't really be taken seriously as anything more than a PR piece. But what do you expect? Director Josie Rourke is Catholic. Her bias is glaringly apparent. Do not mistake this movie for being historically accurate. It's not.

text: To all who followed and replied my post here I would like to clarify some things. My post was supposed to be ironic because I know it does not match people's expectations and, in most cases,  it¬¥s beyond their knowledge. According to Miranda Kaufmann, the author of Black Tudors, there were black people present at the royal courts of Henry VII, Henry VIII, Elizabeth I and James I, and in the households of Sir Walter Raleigh and William Cecil.   I am no researcher but very interested in the subject. So far, I have not read anything that convinced me that there would have been black or asian NOBILITY in England or Scotland during this period of time with the influence of the regents. For my part, movies like this are my taste. Everyone knows that no movies are historically correct and can only be based on real people and events. Gemma Chan (the Asian woman) plays Bess of Hardwick, a person who has lived. Some people will never be correct to change ethnicity. I would never want to see a black man playing Hitler, nor a white man playing Nelson Mandela. I find it hard to believe any character in this movie destroys the experience of it. If it does, then maybe it's more about the viewer than the movie.

text: Why does everyone care about accuracies? Did you really expect it to be totally accurate? Plus you are judging it by only watching the trailer! Did you pirate it or something or go to the special screening? I mean what's wrong with a historical fiction movie? It's been done before. We're really not witnessing anything new. No history movie that's based in the medieval times are ever going to be completely historically accurate. That's damn near impossible. I mean if you ask me, the real only problems are Mary's accent and the scene with her and Elizabeth meeting which could very well be a dream sequence. Even if it isn't, the other trailer shows that Elizabeth says they're meeting in secret so at least they're addressing the known knowledge of them never meeting. As for the accent, this movie isn't the only portrayal of Mary that gave her the wrong accent. Elizabeth The Golden Age also gave her a Scottish accent and Reign gave her an English accent. Apparently Reign also gave the French English accents from what I heard so why attack this movie over the whole accent thing when it's not even what started it all? There was also another Elizabeth and Mary movie that had them meet. So again, why must this movie get so attacked? One thing this movie got right and other portrayals did not was that Mary actually has red hair while other portrayals like Adelaide Kane and Samantha Morton portrayed her with brown hair. I realize that's a very small detail compared to others but I'm just saying. Reign also portrayed Elizabeth as a much more evil queen then she really was. Again, I'm just saying that there are other history movies with inaccuracies so why must people make it like such a big thing when commenting on this movie?

text: Mary Queen of Scots is my ultimate favorite historical figure. I know almost everything about her. Spoiler Alert she dies beheaded.   Couple of Fun Facts: Mary had an a French accent because of the time she spent in France betrothed to the Dauphin of France. She was queen at the age of 6 days Elizabeth and Mary never met but they are buried next to each other in Westminster Abbey She married her cousin Lord Darnley She produced the first heir James I that would rule and unite Scotland and England She was a prisoner for 19 years in England Married three times Blamed for the death of her second husband She was a Catholic ruling a Protestant Nation Many thought that after "Bloody Mary" died, Mary Queen of Scots was the rightful ruler not Elizabeth I Both Elizabeth and Mary were disliked by John Knox who believed that women had no business ruling.   While I know this movie won't be historically accurate, after all it is Entertainment. I welcome anything that has to with Mary Queen of Scots, I encourage anybody to go their local Library or bookstore and read about her, her history is full of rich drama.

text: OMG I can't with all these people complaining about POC existing in Europe during the Tudor Period. Let's just quickly review a timeline here...   Elizabeth I was the daughter of Henry VIII and Anne Boleyn.  Henry's first wife was Catherine of Aragon, whose parents were King Ferdinand and Queen Isabella of Spain, who also controlled the vast majority of the Holy Roman Empire in Europe and who commissioned nearly all the great explorers of the time.  Hell, Christopher Columbus had already been to the New World and back a century before this film takes place and that was the last area of the globe to be discovered. Travel to Asia had been going on for several centuries prior.  And Africa was always most easily accessible continent by sea to the south of Europe. Northern Africans and Southern Europeans had been on one another's lands since water vessels were engineered by primitive humans.  Nobody is able to make the logical conclusion that during this late period of European expansion and exploration, that people came back along with goods? The slave trade didn't begin in the 1600s in the New World. It was WELL underway at this point in history. And not just slavery but interracial relationships as well as those seeking opportunities in a different part of the world.   And I don't remember anyone bitching about Morgan Freeman starring in Robin Hood back in 1991. And that film takes place 400 years before this one does.   Heads out of asses, people.

text: BALDERDASH. Anachronistic, ahistorical, fictitious nonsense. Entire conversations and episodes that never happened and a lazy schoolboy's grasp of history. Mary was brought up primarily in France and spoke English with a French accent, rather as Bonnie Prince Charlie, in the 1740's, also did not have a a Scots burr at all. He was brought up in Rome and spoke English with an Italian accent. Mary would appear here to be dealt as much cinematic injustice in this laughable waste of celluloid as ever she was dealt in life. And Sub-Saharan Africans and even Asians in Elizabethan Britain? God's Teeth, why not throw in Eskimos and Japanese geishas, too? Don't they deserve to be represented? Jesus, this "creative casting" nonsense runs insanely amok these days. There was a time, kids, called the 1980's, when people still knew how to make movies. This is crap, cobbled to-gether by teenagers, seemingly. If you want to know about this period in British history, stay the Hell home and read some books on the subject---written by real scholars and published no later than the 1970's. Christ, this makes "Braveheart" look like Shakespeare.

text: Let's be clear on black people in this film. this period was the 1500s. The Europeans were making headways in worldwide exploration. Columbus found the new world in 1492 as an example. Europeans were sailing around the Cape of Africa in the early 1500s towards India and the east indies.  Black people were recorded as being in the tudor royal courts as servents, musicians and entertainers to some capacity. No doubt taken from Africa in this period. Never though were they recorded as parliamentary advisers or nobility in the 1500s. The danger we have with re-writing history and putting black people in positions of power in northern European society is that Ur sweeping under the rug the hardship, sweat and blood that Africans has to endure under European colonolism and expansionism. Your painting a rosy picture when on fact it was just the opposite. Come the 1600s England used black Africans in large numbers for assisting the colonial settlers in North America.

text: Its too bad that Hollywood continues with its agenda of forced diversity at the expense of quality story telling and entertainment.  This really could've been a great opportunity to bring to life one of the most important events in English history that shaped not only the balance of power in Europe, but, in the New World as well.  Had Mary Queen of Scots prevailed in her plots to assassinate Elizabeth, who knows how that would've impacted England's conquest of North America?   Without Elizabeth's charter for Sir Walter Raleigh to colonize and claim "Virginia" in the name of England, perhaps France or Spain would've been first to claim it?  Who knows?    In any case, its a shame the film makers could not see past the necrotic influence of political correctness and give this piece of history the proper respect it warrants and deserves.

text: Oh please. Mary Queen of Scots, a romantic warrior heroine tragically executed by the jealous English queen? Mary's downfall was entirely her own fault. Stupid woman spent most of her life bumbling from one catastrophic mistake to another. Declared herself queen of England purely on the basis of being Catholic (doing herself NO favours with Elizabeth even then), alienated her nobles, married a spoilt immature drunk, arranged his murder when she grew tired of him, acquitted the murderer then MARRIED him, was forced to abdicate by her exasperated nobles, escaped house arrest where she would have been comparatively safe, barged into England uninvited where she had little to no friends or supporters, to throw herself on Elizabeth's mercy; only to openly and in cold blood plot to assassinate her and usurp her throne (English spies read every one of her smuggled letters, by the end she had zero to say in her own defence save for "I'm a queen, you can't touch me!" and "I'm a CATHOLIC MARTYR") Elizabeth had no choice but to execute her, a decision that she AGONISED over, and still brought down the wrath of Spain upon her (Liz won that one too though.) Mary had not a tenth of Elizabeth's shrewdness, statecraft, foreign policy or common sense. All she  had going for her were beauty and charm, and they deserted her quickly enough. She'd grown up cosseted and pampered as well as Catholic in France, how could she hope to rule Protestant Scotland or her subjects? No Hollywood-ised overdramatic "adaptation" will change the facts.  Show less

text: The writers certainly used up a large chunk of poetic license on this one.  The two Queens never met in person, nor is there any indication in any of Mary's letters that she addressed Elizabeth as an inferior.  Mary may have thought it, but she always addressed Elizabeth in writing as her sister Queen and cousin throughout her long years of captivity and prior.  Mary, of course, was Queen Regnant of Scotland long before Elizabeth came to the throne of England.  Mary was also a former Queen Consort of France, then Queen Dowager.  Mary was an undisputed Princess of the Blood Royal in the legitimate line, while Elizabeth's legitimacy was questionable at best.

text: Some of y‚Äôall don‚Äôt understand that Catalina de Aragon (Katherine of Aragon, first wife of Elizabeth‚Äôs father) brung African servants with her when she came to England to marry Henry the 8th‚Äôs older brother Author. Author died and she was left a widow. She did have to sell her African servants and jewelry to get decent food but when Henry the 8th‚Äôs father Henry the 7th died he became King and married Catalina (Katherine). When she became Queen of England she brought back her loyal African servants and she also had English ladies in waiting like the (in)famous Anne Boleyn. When Henry divorced her some of her servants were left behind and served Anne Boleyn. It went on to Jane Seymour, to Anne of Cleves, to Katherine Howard, to Katherine Parr, to Queen Mary, and then to Queen Elizabeth. They also started having an ambassador from African tribes. Queen Elizabeth might have killed her own cousin and many many many of her own soldiers and Catholics but she was still ahead of her time.

text: I hate they make Elisabeth look like SHE was the one wasting away when in reality Mary was bald and wore a wig and when she was decapitated her wig came off. Many of Queen Elizabeth's servants said she had a full head of red hair. So it really bothers me they try and make Mary the "pretty" one when although Elizabeth was "swarthy" she was said to be beautiful. Mary was raised to be a wife not a queen to rule. Scotland didn't even WANT her. She is the one who kept attempting to attack her cousin because she "felt" like Elizabeth didn't deserve the throne and the she had the backing of the Catholic Church.  This is just SO inaccurate I can't believe the actresses even agreed to the film. It's a joke.   I'm really fed up with all these stories creating Elizabeth as some villain when in reality she was a very sad and abused woman who never once got anything she desired. Her price to live and be queen was being sexually abused, giving up her one love, never knowing her mother, losing her father and all her siblings and yet it's still easier for movie writers to paint her a villain. Even though she may have been responsible for May's death she regretted that the most until the day she died. She was completely beside herself losing her but she really honestly had no other options! Mary clearly manipulated Elisabeth who needed a friend. Mary was never a good woman.   I urge some of these screenplay writers to watch a freaking documentary if it's just too much to have to read about it.
